\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{The three workpoints.}{13}{section*.25}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Cross-regime cap-binding profile (16 cards, 5 seeds, mean values). The three workpoints differ along a single axis --- how heavily the bandwidth cap binds the baseline schedulers. The \emph  {offset-infeasible rate} counts tasks for which phase-shift finds no offset in $[0, D_{\max }]$ that keeps the forecast peak below the cap; such a task is still admitted at offset $0$ (no task is ever dropped, cf.\ Section~\ref {sec:eval:setup}), but phase-shift cannot relieve its contribution to congestion.}}{14}{table.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:q2_regime_profile}{{6}{14}{Cross-regime cap-binding profile (16 cards, 5 seeds, mean values). The three workpoints differ along a single axis --- how heavily the bandwidth cap binds the baseline schedulers. The \emph {offset-infeasible rate} counts tasks for which phase-shift finds no offset in $[0, D_{\max }]$ that keeps the forecast peak below the cap; such a task is still admitted at offset $0$ (no task is ever dropped, cf.\ Section~\ref {sec:eval:setup}), but phase-shift cannot relieve its contribution to congestion}{table.6}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Cross-regime $\Delta $CV under \textsc  {+ps} (16 cards, 5 seeds, $(off\!-\!on)/off \times 100$; positive $=$ phase-shift reduces CV). Phase-shift lowers CV for \emph  {every} policy in the non-binding (B) and light (C) regimes. In the binding regime~A the effect is mixed: BestFit/DRF and P2C still improve, but the round-robin baseline and the already-spatially-balanced \textsc  {stps-spatial} regress, because a tight cap has pre-flattened their served load and any offset scatters it off that floor. Dispersion is thus a sign-varying side-effect of phase-shift, not a second objective; congestion (the target) moves one way only.}}{14}{table.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:q2_regime_cv}{{7}{14}{Cross-regime $\Delta $CV under \textsc {+ps} (16 cards, 5 seeds, $(off\!-\!on)/off \times 100$; positive $=$ phase-shift reduces CV). Phase-shift lowers CV for \emph {every} policy in the non-binding (B) and light (C) regimes. In the binding regime~A the effect is mixed: BestFit/DRF and P2C still improve, but the round-robin baseline and the already-spatially-balanced \textsc {stps-spatial} regress, because a tight cap has pre-flattened their served load and any offset scatters it off that floor. Dispersion is thus a sign-varying side-effect of phase-shift, not a second objective; congestion (the target) moves one way only}{table.7}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{Phase-shift's CV effect depends on the cap.}{14}{section*.26}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Cross-regime direction summary for the remaining Stage-B metrics (16 cards). Phase-shift relieves congestion only where the cap binds (A,~C); its CV effect is uniformly favourable in the loose regimes (B,~C) and mixed under the hard-binding cap (A), where round-robin and \textsc  {stps-spatial} regress while BestFit/P2C still improve. The throughput cost is set by the offset budget's ratio to the steady-state window and the cap-rejection rate.}}{14}{table.8}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:q2_regime_multi}{{8}{14}{Cross-regime direction summary for the remaining Stage-B metrics (16 cards). Phase-shift relieves congestion only where the cap binds (A,~C); its CV effect is uniformly favourable in the loose regimes (B,~C) and mixed under the hard-binding cap (A), where round-robin and \textsc {stps-spatial} regress while BestFit/P2C still improve. The throughput cost is set by the offset budget's ratio to the steady-state window and the cap-rejection rate}{table.8}{}}
